# Tests — npm only

The `web-client.test.ts` suite can hang and consume 2–3 GB RAM if stale runners are left behind. Direct `npx tsx --test` / `node --test` **does not** run the stale-runner cleanup.

## Commands

| Task | Command |
|------|---------|
| Full suite | `npm test` (`pretest` kills stale runners first) |
| Web client only | `npm run test:web` |
| Before a rare manual run | `node scripts/dev/kill-stale-test-runners.mjs` |

## Why not direct tsx/node --test

- `pretest` → `scripts/dev/kill-stale-test-runners.mjs` terminates orphaned test processes from prior runs.
- Skipping npm bypasses that hook; zombies keep RAM and can block ports or skew results.
- CI and local acceptance assume the npm entry points above.

## Forbidden

- `npx tsx --test tests/…`
- `node --test tests/…` without running the kill script first

## When debugging one file

Prefer `npm run test:web` if the file is in that subset. Otherwise run the kill script once, then use npm — not raw tsx against the full tree.
